 "state_of_play": {
  "heading": "The state of play",
  "body": [
   "For all the model's confidence in the favorite, this has been the opposite of a chalk tournament. Rawhides have held up their end \u2014 still a commanding <b>91.1%</b> to win it \u2014 but everything behind them has been chaos: a #2 seed knocked out early, the six-season Pilsner dynasty gone, a 12-seed Cinderella in Route 101, and a 7-seed in Pocket Fizz that flatly refuses to read the seed lines. With the field down to <b>3</b>, the bracket has split into two very different movies.",
   "On the A-side it's coronation-or-spoiler: <b>Rawhides sit one win from the hot seat</b>, with only Bus Stop in the way \u2014 and four seasons of history saying Rawhides own that matchup when it counts (<b>5-1</b> all-time, and a perfect <b>2-0</b> in the playoffs). On the B-side it's a survival gauntlet: <b>El Farolito</b>, the fallen 2-seed, is trying to claw all the way back \u2014 and runs straight into <b>Pocket Fizz</b>, the very team that knocked them down in the first place. A revenge rematch with a season on the line.",
   "What keeps it tense even with a heavy favorite is the double-elimination math. Rawhides need just two wins and carry a safety net at every step; whoever emerges from the losers' bracket has to run the table and then beat the A-side finalist <i>twice</i>. Two wins with insurance versus five must-wins through a gauntlet \u2014 that asymmetry is the whole tournament in a sentence. For the trophy to change hands, somebody's long shot has to hit."
  ]
 },
